name: 4-iodotoluene
Reason: The structure of 4-iodotoluene is composed of a benzene ring, a methyl group, and an iodine atom attached to the benzene ring. The basic unit, benzene, has a melting point of 5.5 °C. The methyl group typically raises the melting point due to an increase in the molecular weight and a slight increase in van der Waals forces, this could approximately add about +5 °C. However, the presence of the iodine atom will have a significant impact on the melting point due to its large size and relatively high atomic mass, which substantially increases the van der Waals forces. This could raise the melting point by approximately +70 °C. We must consider that the iodine atom being directly attached to the benzene ring also makes the molecule more polar, which can further increase the melting point due to stronger intermolecular interactions. This additional polarity can be estimated to contribute roughly another +10 °C. Hence, the overall predicted increase in melting point relative to benzene would be a total of +5 °C (methyl group) + +70 °C (iodine mass and van der Waals increase) + +10 °C (increased polarity due to iodine).
